\b 1. Health and Wellbeing\b0\par
28. Even at the outset, I would like to say that the investment on Health\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Infrastructure in this Budget has increased substantially. Progressively, as\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 institutions absorb more, we shall commit more.\par
29. Taking a holistic approach to Health, we focus on strengthening\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 three areas: Preventive, Curative, and Wellbeing.\par
\b Health Systems\b0\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\tx8662 30. A new centrally sponsored scheme, PM AtmaNirbhar Swasth Bharat\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Yojana, will be launched with an outlay of about ` 64,180 crores over 6\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 years. This will develop capacities of primary, secondary, and tertiary care\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Health Systems, strengthen existing national institutions, and create new\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 institutions, to cater to detection and cure of new and emerging diseases.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 This will be in addition to the National Health Mission. The main\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 interventions under the scheme are:\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1 a. Support for 17,788 rural and 11,024 urban Health and Wellness\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Centers\par
b. Setting up integrated public health labs in all districts and 3382 block\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 public health units in 11 states;\par
c. Establishing critical care hospital blocks in 602 districts and 12\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 central institutions;\par
d. Strengthening of the National Centre for Disease Control (NCDC), its\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 5 regional branches and 20 metropolitan health surveillance units;\par
e. Expansion of the Integrated Health Information Portal to all\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 States/UTs to connect all public health labs;\par
f. Operationalisation of 17 new Public Health Units and strengthening\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 of 33 existing Public Health Units at Points of Entry, that is at 32\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Airports, 11 Seaports and 7 land crossings;\par
g. Setting up of 15 Health Emergency Operation Centers and 2 mobile\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 hospitals; and\par
h. Setting up of a national institution for One Health, a Regional\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Research Platform for WHO South East Asia Region, 9 Bio-Safety\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Level III laboratories and 4 regional National Institutes for Virology.\par
Nutrition\par
31. To strengthen nutritional content, delivery, outreach, and outcome,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 we will merge the Supplementary Nutrition Programme and the Poshan\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Abhiyan and launch the Mission Poshan 2.0. We shall adopt an intensified\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 strategy to improve nutritional outcomes across 112 Aspirational Districts.\par
\b Universal Coverage of Water Supply\par
\b0 32. The World Health Organisation has repeatedly stressed the\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 importance of clean water, sanitation, and clean environment, as a pre\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 requisite to achieving universal health.\par
33. The Jal Jeevan Mission (Urban), will be launched. It aims at universal\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 water supply in all 4,378 Urban Local Bodies with 2.86 crores household tap\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 connections, as well as liquid waste management in 500 AMRUT cities. It\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 will be implemented over 5 years, with an outlay of `2,87,000 crores.\par
\b Swachch Bharat, Swasth Bharat\par
\b0 34. For further swachhta of urban India, we intend to focus on complete\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 faecal sludge management and waste water treatment, source segregation\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 of garbage, reduction in single-use plastic, reduction in air pollution by\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 effectively managing waste from construction-and-demolition activities and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 bio-remediation of all legacy dump sites. The Urban Swachh Bharat Mission\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 2.0 will be implemented with a total financial allocation of `1,41,678 crores\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 over a period of 5 years from 2021-2026.\par
\b Clean Air\b0\par
35. To tackle the burgeoning problem of air pollution, I propose to\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 provide an amount of `2,217 crores for 42 urban centres with a million-plus\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 population in this budget. \par
\b\f0\lang2057 S\f2\lang9 crapping Policy\par
\b0 36. We are separately announcing a voluntary vehicle scrapping policy,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 to phase out old and unfit vehicles. This will help in encouraging fuelefficient, environment friendly vehicles, thereby reducing\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 vehicular\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 pollution and oil import bill. Vehicles would undergo fitness tests in\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 automated fitness centres after 20 years in case of personal vehicles, and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 after 15 years in case of commercial vehicles. Details of the scheme will be\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 separately shared by the Ministry.\par
\b Vaccines\b0\par
37. The Pneumococcal Vaccine, a Made in India product, is presently\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 limited to only 5 states will be rolled out across the country. This will avert\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 more than 50,000 child deaths annually.\par
38. I have provided `35,000 crores for Covid-19 vaccine in BE 2021-22. I\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 am committed to provide further funds if required.\par
39. The Budget outlay for Health and Wellbeing is `2,23,846 crores in BE\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 2021-22 as against this year\rquote s BE of `94,452 crores an increase of 137\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 percentage. The details of the same are at Annexure I of the Speech.\par
\par
\b 2. Physical and Financial Capital and Infrastructure\par
AtmaNirbhar Bharat \endash  Production Linked Incentive scheme (PLI)\par
\b0 40. For a USD 5 trillion economy, our manufacturing sector has to grow\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 in double digits on a sustained basis. Our manufacturing companies need to\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 become an integral part of global supply chains, possess core competence\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 and cutting-edge technology. To achieve all of the above, PLI schemes to\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 create manufacturing global champions for an AtmaNirbhar Bharat have\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 been announced for 13 sectors. For this, the government has committed\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 nearly `1.97 lakh crores, over 5 years starting FY 2021-22. This initiative will\par
help bring scale and size in key sectors, create and nurture global\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 champions and provide jobs to our youth.\par
\b Textiles\b0\par
41. To enable the textile industry to become globally competitive,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 attract large investments and boost employment generation, a scheme of\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Mega Investment Textiles Parks (MITRA) will be launched in addition to the\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 PLI scheme. This will create world class infrastructure with plug and play\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 facilities to enable create global champions in exports. 7 Textile Parks will\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 be established over 3 years.\par
\b Infrastructure\b0\par
42. The National Infrastructure Pipeline (NIP) which I announced in\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 December 2019 is the first-of-its-kind, whole-of-government exercise ever\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 undertaken by Government of India. The NIP was launched with 6835\par
projects; the project pipeline has now expanded to 7,400 projects. Around\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 217 projects worth `1.10 lakh crores under some key infrastructure\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Ministries have been completed.\par
43. The NIP is a specific target which this government is committed to\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 achieving over the coming years. It will require a major increase in funding\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 both from the government and the financial sector. In this Budget, I\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 propose to take concrete steps to do this, in three ways:\par
44. Firstly, by creating the institutional structures; secondly, by a big\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 thrust on monetizing assets, and thirdly by enhancing the share of capital\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 expenditure in central and state budgets.\par
\b Infrastructure financing - Development Financial Institution (DFI)\b0\par
45. Infrastructure needs long term debt financing. A professionally\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 managed Development Financial Institution is necessary to act as a\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 provider, enabler and catalyst for infrastructure financing. Accordingly, I\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 shall introduce a Bill to set up a DFI. I have provided a sum of `20,000 crores\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 to capitalise this institution. The ambition is to have a lending portfolio of at\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 least `5 lakh crores for this DFI in three years time.\par
46. Debt Financing of InVITs and REITs by Foreign Portfolio Investors will\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 be enabled by making suitable amendments in the relevant legislations. This\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 will further ease access of finance to InVITS and REITs thus augmenting\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 funds for infrastructure and real estate sectors.\par
\b Asset Monetisation\b0\par
47. Monetizing operating public infrastructure assets is a very important\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 financing option for new infrastructure construction. A \ldblquote National\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Monetization Pipeline\rdblquote  of potential brownfield infrastructure assets will be\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 launched. An Asset Monetization dashboard will also be created for\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 tracking the progress and to provide visibility to investors. Some important\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 measures in the direction of monetisation are:\par
a. National Highways Authority of India and PGCIL each have\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 sponsored one InvIT that will attract\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 international and domestic\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 institutional investors. Five operational roads with an estimated\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 enterprise value of ` 5,000 crores are being transferred to the NHAI\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 InvIT. Similarily, transmission assets of a value of `7,000 crores will\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 be transferred to the PGCIL InvIT.\par
b. Railways will monetise Dedicated Freight Corridor assets for\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 operations and maintenance, after commissioning.\par
c. The next lot of Airports will be monetised for operations and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 management concession.\par
d. Other core infrastructure assets that will be rolled out under the\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Asset Monetization Programme are: (i) NHAI Operational Toll Roads\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 (ii) Transmission Assets of PGCIL (iii) Oil and Gas Pipelines of GAIL,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 IOCL and HPCL (iv) AAI Airports in Tier II and III cities, (v) Other\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Railway Infrastructure Assets (vi) Warehousing Assets of CPSEs such\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 as Central Warehousing Corporation and NAFED among others and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 (vii) Sports Stadiums.\par
\b Sharp Increase in Capital Budget\b0\par
48. In the BE 2020-21, we had provided `4.12 lakh crores for Capital\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Expenditure. It was our effort that in spite of resource crunch we should\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 spend more on capital and we are likely to end the year at around `4.39\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 lakh crores which I have provided in the RE 2020-21. For 2021-22, I propose\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 a sharp increase in capital expenditure and thus have provided `5.54 lakh\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 crores which is 34.5% more than the BE of 2020-21. Of this, I have kept a\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 sum of more than `44,000 crores in the Budget head of the Department of\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Economic Affairs to be provided for projects/programmes/departments\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 that show good progress on Capital Expenditure and are in need of further\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 funds. Over and above this expenditure, we would also be providing more\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 than `2 lakh crores to States and Autonomous Bodies for their Capital\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Expenditure.\par
49. We will also work out specific mechanisms to nudge States to spend\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 more of their budget on creation of infrastructure.\par
\b Roads and Highways Infrastructure\b0\par
50. More than 13,000 km length of roads, at a cost of `3.3 lakh crores,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 has already been awarded under the `5.35 lakh crores Bharatmala\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 Pariyojana project of which 3,800 kms have been constructed. By March\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 2022, we would be awarding another 8,500 kms and complete an additional\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 11,000 kms of national highway corridors.\par
51. To further augment road infrastructure, more economic corridors\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 are also being planned. Some are:\par
a. 3,500 km of National Highway works in the state of Tamil Nadu at an\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 investment of `1.03 lakh crores. These include Madurai-Kollam\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 corridor, Chittoor-Thatchur corridor. Construction will start next\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang9 year.\par
