\b Iron and Steel\b0\par
180. MSMEs and other user industries have been severely hit by a recent\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 sharp rise in iron and steel prices. Therefore, we are reducing Customs duty\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 uniformly to 7.5% on semis, flat, and long products of non-alloy, alloy, and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 stainless steels. To provide relief to metal re-cyclers, mostly MSMEs, I am\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 exempting duty on steel scrap for a period up to 31st March, 2022. Further,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 I am also revoking ADD and CVD on certain steel products. Also, to provide\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 relief to copper recyclers, I am reducing duty on copper scrap from 5% to\par
2.5%.\par
\b Textile\b0\par
181. The Textiles Sector generates employment and contributes\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 significantly to the economy. There is a need to rationalize duties on raw\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 material inputs to manmade textiles. We are now bringing nylon chain on\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 par with polyester and other man-made fibers. We are uniformly reducing the BCD rates on caprolactam, nylon chips and nylon fiber & yarn to 5%.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 This will help the textile industry, MSMEs, and exports, too.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033\par
\b Chemicals\b0\par
182. We have calibrated customs duty rates on chemicals to encourage\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 domestic value addition and to remove inversions. Apart from other items,\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 we are reducing customs duty on Naptha to 2.5% to correct inversion.\par
\b Gold and Silver\b0\par
183. Gold and silver presently attract a basic customs duty of 12.5%.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 Since the duty was raised from 10% in July 2019, prices of precious metals\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 have risen sharply. To bring it closer to previous levels, we are \f0\lang2057 r\f2\lang1033 ationalizing\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 custom duty on gold and silver.\par
\b Renewable Energy\par
\b0 184. In Part A, we have already acknowledged that solar energy has huge\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 promise for India. To build up domestic capacity, we will notify a phased\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 manufacturing plan for solar cells and solar panels. At \f0\lang2057 p\f2\lang1033 resent, to encourage\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 domestic production, we are raising duty on solar invertors from 5% to 20%,\par
and on solar lanterns from 5% to 15%.\par
\b Capital Equipment and Auto Parts\b0\par
185. There is immense potential in manufacturing heavy capital\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 equipment domestically. We will comprehensively review the rate structure\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 in due course. However, we are revising duty rates on certain items\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 immediately. We propose to withdraw exemptions on tunnel boring\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 machine. It will attract a customs duty of 7.5%; and its parts a duty of 2.5%.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 We are raising customs duty on certain auto parts to 15% to bring them on\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 par with general rate on auto parts.\par
\b MSME Products\b0\par
186. We are proposing certain changes to benefit MSMEs. We are\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 increasing duty from 10% to 15% on steel screws and plastic builder wares.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 On prawn feed we increase it from 5% to 15%. We are rationalizing\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 exemption on import of duty-free items as an incentive to exporters of garments, leather, and handicraft items. Almost all these items are made\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 domestically by our MSMEs. We are withdrawing exemption on imports of\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 certain kind of leathers as they are domestically produced in good quantity\par
and quality, mostly by MSMEs. We are also raising customs duty on finished\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 synthetic gem stones to encourage their domestic processing.\par
\b Agriculture Products\b0\par
187. To benefit farmers, we are raising customs duty on cotton from nil\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 to 10% and on raw silk and silk yarn from 10% to 15%. We are also\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 withdrawing end-use based concession on denatured ethyl alcohol.\par
Currently, rates are being uniformly calibrated to 15% on items like maize\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 bran, rice bran oil cake, and animal feed additives.\par
188. There is an immediate need to improve agricultural infrastructure\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 so that we produce more, while also conserving and processing agricultural\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 output efficiently. This will ensure enhanced remuneration for our farmers.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 To earmark resources for this purpose, I propose an Agriculture\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 Infrastructure and Development Cess (AIDC) on a small number of items.\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 However, while applying this cess, we have taken care not to put additional\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 burden on consumers on most items.\par
\b Rationalization of Procedures and Easing of Compliance\b0\par
189. For their judicious application, we propose certain changes in the\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 provisions relating to ADD and CVD levies. To complete Customs\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 investigations, we are prescribing definite timelines. In 2020, we rolled out\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 the Turant Customs initiative, which brought in Faceless, Paperless, and\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 Contactless Customs measures. With effect from September 2020, we have\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 implemented a new procedure for administration of Rules of Origin. This\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 has helped in putting a check on misuse of FTAs.\par
190. The specific details of direct and indirect tax changes proposed are\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 listed in the Annexure to my speech.\par
191. Mr. Speaker Sir, with these words I commend the Budget to this\f0\lang2057  \f2\lang1033 august House.\par
